[Review by unstubbable]: It's nice how simple and clean the final commit is because of the preparatory work that went into the preceding PRs.

One (possibly naïve) question about the causality:

> Using the same AbortSignal to notify data sources is the intended protocol, but Fizz cannot distinguish a rejection caused by that signal from any unrelated rejection that happens to occur during the abort window.

What if we made the contract so that a rejected wakeable would need to use the abort signal's reason as its `cause`? That would allow us to ignore unrelated rejections that just coincidentally happened to occur between starting and finishing the abort, wouldn't it?

E.g. (building on your "Intended Usage" example):

```js
signal.addEventListener('abort', () => {
  reject(new TimeoutError('optional recommendations timed out', {cause: signal.reason}));
});
```

And then in `pingRejectedTask` we could compare `error.cause` with `request.fatalError`, I suppose. | [Review by Credok12]: ok

body:
## Summary

Fixes #34752, #34194, #35762

### The bug

The compiler hoists property accesses from inside closures (event handlers, hook callbacks, returned functions) into memoization cache key checks that run during render. When the base object is nullable, this causes a runtime `TypeError` — even though the user's source code is perfectly safe.

For example, this cart page from the [iFixit workaround PR](https://github.com/iFixit/ifixit/pull/61341):

```tsx
function CartPageView() {
  const cart = useCart(); // cart.data is null until loaded
  const [promoCode, setPromoCode] = useState('');

  const handleCheckout = async () => {
    await processPayment({
      price: cart.data.totals.price,
      itemCount: cart.data.lineItems.length,
      promoCode,
    });
  };

  if (!cart.data) return <CartSkeleton />;

  return (
    <div>
      <LineItems items={cart.data.lineItems} />
      <span>{cart.data.totals.price}</span>
      <input value={promoCode} onChange={e => setPromoCode(e.target.value)} />
      <button onClick={handleCheckout}>Checkout</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The source code is safe: `handleCheckout` only runs when the user clicks, and the `if (!cart.data) return` guard prevents the button from rendering while the cart is loading. [But the compiler generates:](https://playground.react.dev/#-xZFwR8Eo7wlRgyk5wgyDMw83yqlvnnvugImAAWQhdYeBAI1TFAvgVTAP8wH7BAjAXKAl0wVd10KHIu3AYoIBYD4rAQFkjTAFA0GI80gA)

```js
const cart = useCart();
const [promoCode, setPromoCode] = useState("");

// Cache check runs BEFORE the null guard — crashes when cart.data is null
if (
  $[0] !== cart.data.lineItems.length ||  // TypeError
  $[1] !== cart.data.totals.price ||
  $[2] !== promoCode
) {
  t0 = async () => { /* ... */ };
  $[0] = cart.data.lineItems.length;
  $[1] = cart.data.totals.price;
  // ...
}

// The null guard comes AFTER — too late
if (!cart.data) return <CartSkeleton />;
```

The compiler saw `cart.data.totals.price` and `cart.data.lineItems.length` inside `handleCheckout`, concluded that `cart.data` must be non-null, and hoisted those property accesses into render-time cache keys. But `handleCheckout` doesn't run during render — it runs later when the user clicks. The non-null assumption is invalid.

Note that the render-time code a...

